(21. Value numbering) Tj
T*
(Source: Max Bernstein's Blog | Published: Sat, 04 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000) Tj
T*
(Link: https://bernsteinbear.com/blog/value-numbering/?utm_source=rss) Tj
T*
(Welcome back to compiler land. Today we?re going to talk about value numbering , which is like) Tj
T*
(SSA, but more. Static single assignment \(SSA\) gives names to values: every expression has a) Tj
T*
(name, and each name corresponds to exactly one expression. It transforms programs like this: x) Tj
T*
(= 0 x = x + 1 x = x + 1 where the variable x is assigned more than once in the program text,) Tj
T*
(into programs like this: v0 = 0 v1 = v0 + 1 v2 = v1 + 1 where each assignment to x has been) Tj
T*
(replaced with an assignment to a new fresh name. It?s great because it makes clear the) Tj
T*
(differences between the two x + 1 expressions. Though they textually look similar, they compute) Tj
T*
(different values. The first computes 1 and the second computes 2. In this example, it is not) Tj
T*
(possible to substitute in a variable and re-use the value of x + 1 , because the x s are) Tj
T*
(different. But what if we see two ?textually? identical instructions in SSA? That sounds much) Tj
T*
(more promising than non-SSA because the transformation into SSA form has removed \(much of\) the) Tj
T*
(statefulness of it all. When can we re-use the result? Identifying instructions that are known) Tj
T*
(at compile-time to always produce the same value at run-time is called value number...) Tj
T*
() Tj
